text:
Madison:Wisconsin Public Service Commission has issued the following document
:

WPL submits the following information as a part of its Application for a
Certificate of Authority (Application) to acquire and operate six solar
electric generating facilities located in Wisconsin. One of those six
facilities is the North Rock Project (Project), an approximately 50-megawatt
alternating current (MWAC) solar electric generation facility, which will be
located in the Town of Fulton, Rock County, Wisconsin. North Rock Solar, LLC
(North Rock), a wholly owned subsidiary of Geronimo Energy, LLC (Geronimo), is
currently developing the Project, but WPL intends to acquire and operate the
Project, subject to receipt of the Public Service Commission of Wisconsin's
(Commission) approval in this proceeding.

To aid the Commission and Wisconsin Department of Natural Resource's (WDNR)
review and permitting of the Application, WPL has prepared this appendix,
which provides an overview of the Project's environmental, community, land
use, and other site-specific impacts. The information included herein is based
on the guidance provided in the Commission's Draft Application Filing
Requirements for Solar Energy Projects (Solar AFR). Some of the information
called for in the Solar AFR (e.g., project need and economic analysis) is
presented in the main body of WPL's Application, whereas other information is
unavailable at this time.

WPL has made its best efforts to provide the Commission with as much
information as possible regarding this Project to facilitate the Commission's
review of the Application. However, construction is not scheduled to begin
until July 2022 and the Project design is still preliminary in nature.
Accordingly, the information presented in this appendix is based on
information known to WPL at this time and is subject to change as Project
development proceeds and the Project design is finalized.

1\. PROJECT DESCRIPTION AND OVERVIEW

1.1 GENERAL PROJECT LOCATION AND DESCRIPTION OF PROJECT AND PROJECT AREA

The proposed Project will be located in the Town of Fulton, Township 4N, Range
12E, Section 17, Rock County, spanning multiple different parcels with
different property owners. The Project will be located in an area bounded by
County Road M (to the south), Pomeroy Road (to the north), and Staff road (to
the west). North Rock possesses signed landowner agreements for the parcels on
which the Project solar panels, substation, laydown yard, transformers,
junction boxes, and collection system are currently proposed to be located.
WPL has included a map of the project location within Appendix C-1 - Fig
1.1.2, 4.1.1, and 4.1.2.

The Project will be interconnected to the high-voltage transmission grid
through a generator tie-line located in Town of Fulton, Township 4N, Range
12E, Sections 5, 8, and 9. The transmission line will consist of an
approximately 1.5 mile, 69-kilovolt (kV) transmission line that will extend
north from the Project and to American Transmission Company's (ATC) Sheepskin
69 kV substation. North Rock has obtained easements for construction of the
transmission line, all of which will continue to be farmed.

There are currently lease options or transmission easement agreements for the
Project

2

and the gen-tie line over parcels that contain approximately 907 acres of
land. Based on the current Project design, WPL intends to lease and obtain
easements over approximately 478 acres of land for the Project pursuant to
these agreements (Project Area). The Project facilities (i.e., arrays,
inverters, collection system, substation, access roads, and gen-tie line) will
occupy approximately 458 acres of land. Refer to Table 1 for additional
information regarding the scope of the Project.

1.2 OWNERSHIP

Project ownership is addressed in Section V of the Application.

1.3 PROJECT NEED/PURPOSE

The need for and economic analysis supporting the Project is addressed in
Section IV of the Application.

1.4 ALTERNATIVES

1.4.1 Supply Alternatives

An analysis of Project alternatives is addressed in Section IV of the
Application.

1.4.2 Project Area Selection

As mentioned, North Rock, a wholly owned subsidiary of Geronimo, is currently
developing the Project. North Rock identified the area for the Project based
on availability of suitable land, interconnection suitability, minimal
environmental impacts, and the surrounding community, as discussed in greater
detail below:

* Land Availability and Infrastructure: Large tracts of undeveloped lands are typically utilized for utility-scale solar facilities. The Project Area is mostly agricultural land that has been cultivated for grain. The Project Area is also adjacent to nearby roads and highways--such as County Road (CR) M and U.S. Route (US) 14--that are suitable for equipment and material delivery during construction.

* Interconnection Suitability: One primary factor in site selection for utility-scale solar development is availably of existing electric infrastructure necessary to connect a project to the power grid. Preferred injection points are found where the existing electrical infrastructure is robust, thereby minimizing the interconnection facility costs and network upgrades frequently attributed to new generating facilities. Projects where land is available near points of interconnection are prioritized.

Prior to submitting an interconnection request into the Midcontinent
Independent System Operator (MISO) queue, North Rock evaluated existing
transmission facilities in

3

the area for available capacity and stability for a utility-scale solar
project. It was determined that the Sheepskin 69-kV substation would have
capacity for a solar project of at least 50 MW without triggering significant
costly upgrades. On March 8, 2018, North Rock submitted an interconnection
request to MISO to interconnect into the Sheepskin 69 kV substation. The North
Rock Solar Project was given MISO queue number J1188. Additional details
regarding the Project's interconnection status are provided in Section 2.5,
below.

* Environmental Considerations: A preliminary analysis was completed to screen for environmental factors including, but not limited to, wetlands, waterways, endangered species, critical habitat, floodplain, and cultural and historic resources. The land on which the Project will be located has few environmental constraints and those factors identified can be avoided by placement of the solar photovoltaic (PV) array.

* Community: It is preferable to site solar projects in communities that welcome those projects and where landowners are interested in hosting solar facilities. The Town of Fulton and Rock County have expressed positive feedback about the Project.

1.5 SITE SELECTION

Refer to Section 1.4 above for a discussion of the individual factors and
characteristics used to select the site on which the Project is being
developed. Table 1 depicts the status of all easement and lease agreements
necessary for construction and operation of the Project. WPL has also included
maps of land ownership within and around the project area in Appendix C-1 -
Fig 4.1.6.2.

1.7 REGULATORY PERMITS AND APPROVALS

Table 3 summarizes the permits and approval types that are anticipated to be
required for the Project. WPL will update the Commission if it determines that
additional permits are necessary. The necessary permits and approvals will be
obtained before commencing construction activities. Copies of official
correspondence with government agencies are included in Appendix C-1. WPL
intends to provide copies of correspondence to and from state, local, and
federal agencies that relate to permit approval, compliance approval, or

2\. TECHNICAL DESCRIPTION, PROJECT AREA, PANEL AND PANEL SITES, AND ANCILLARY
FACILITIES

2.1 ESTIMATED SOLAR RESOURCE AND PROJECTED ENERGY PRODUCTION

To evaluate the solar energy resource for the Project, 12 months of estimated
meteorological data was used. This data was developed utilizing the NREL NSRDB
Typ. Met. Year PSMv3 - 2018 TMY meteo data file collected from Station ID
844313. This data was then supplemented with 23 years of derived satellite
data to fill in any gaps and complete a Model Output Statistic corrected
Typical Meteorological Year. This solar irradiance and climate information was
then used to simulate a typical full year of production with the photovoltaic
systems software ("PVSYST") analysis program.

While the maximum output of the solar farm will be 50 MWAC at the point of
connection, its output may be less at any given time depending on the energy
available from the sun.1 The software program PVSYST was used to simulate the
energy conversion process using model files from the PV module and inverter
manufacturer, historical weather data discussed above, and the parameters that
apply to the solar farm. The net capacity factor for the Project is calculated
to be between 23 and 25 percent, when comparing the nameplate rating (50 MWAC)
to the energy forecasted from the PVSYST model.

The estimated net annual energy production is between approximately 99,000 and
105,000 megawatt hours (MWh). Actual annual energy production output will
depend on final design, site specific features, and annual variability in the
solar resource. Energy losses within the system include electrical losses in
the AC and direct current (DC) electrical collector system, energy conversion
losses within the PV inverters, step-up transformers and various other
equipment, as well as losses due to soiling of the PV modules themselves due
to dust, debris and snow cover. Taking those factors into account, a
reasonable estimate of energy losses range from 15 to 20 percent of the
maximum output, which is consistent with industry-wide estimates.

title: Regulatory update: Wisconsin Public Service Commission; Annette Behnke , has submitted (6680-AE-120 ) Appendix C - Environmental Appendix for North Rock Project (Rev 1 - Redline) WPL Application for Certificate of Authority and Affiliated Interest Approvals.
html:
Madison:Wisconsin Public Service Commission has issued the following document :

WPL submits the following information as a part of its Application for a Certificate of Authority (Application) to acquire and operate six solar electric generating facilities located in Wisconsin. One of those six facilities is the North Rock Project (Project), an approximately 50-megawatt alternating current (MWAC) solar electric generation facility, which will be located in the Town of Fulton, Rock County, Wisconsin. North Rock Solar, LLC (North Rock), a wholly owned subsidiary of Geronimo Energy, LLC (Geronimo), is currently developing the Project, but WPL intends to acquire and operate the Project, subject to receipt of the Public Service Commission of Wisconsin's (Commission) approval in this proceeding.

To aid the Commission and Wisconsin Department of Natural Resource's (WDNR) review and permitting of the Application, WPL has prepared this appendix, which provides an overview of the Project's environmental, community, land use, and other site-specific impacts. The information included herein is based on the guidance provided in the Commission's Draft Application Filing Requirements for Solar Energy Projects (Solar AFR). Some of the information called for in the Solar AFR (e.g., project need and economic analysis) is presented in the main body of WPL's Application, whereas other information is unavailable at this time.

WPL has made its best efforts to provide the Commission with as much information as possible regarding this Project to facilitate the Commission's review of the Application. However, construction is not scheduled to begin until July 2022 and the Project design is still preliminary in nature. Accordingly, the information presented in this appendix is based on information known to WPL at this time and is subject to change as Project development proceeds and the Project design is finalized.

1. PROJECT DESCRIPTION AND OVERVIEW

1.1 GENERAL PROJECT LOCATION AND DESCRIPTION OF PROJECT AND PROJECT AREA

The proposed Project will be located in the Town of Fulton, Township 4N, Range 12E, Section 17, Rock County, spanning multiple different parcels with different property owners. The Project will be located in an area bounded by County Road M (to the south), Pomeroy Road (to the north), and Staff road (to the west). North Rock possesses signed landowner agreements for the parcels on which the Project solar panels, substation, laydown yard, transformers, junction boxes, and collection system are currently proposed to be located. WPL has included a map of the project location within Appendix C-1 - Fig 1.1.2, 4.1.1, and 4.1.2.

The Project will be interconnected to the high-voltage transmission grid through a generator tie-line located in Town of Fulton, Township 4N, Range 12E, Sections 5, 8, and 9. The transmission line will consist of an approximately 1.5 mile, 69-kilovolt (kV) transmission line that will extend north from the Project and to American Transmission Company's (ATC) Sheepskin 69 kV substation. North Rock has obtained easements for construction of the transmission line, all of which will continue to be farmed.

There are currently lease options or transmission easement agreements for the Project

2

and the gen-tie line over parcels that contain approximately 907 acres of land. Based on the current Project design, WPL intends to lease and obtain easements over approximately 478 acres of land for the Project pursuant to these agreements (Project Area). The Project facilities (i.e., arrays, inverters, collection system, substation, access roads, and gen-tie line) will occupy approximately 458 acres of land. 1.4.2 Project Area Selection

As mentioned, North Rock, a wholly owned subsidiary of Geronimo, is currently developing the Project. North Rock identified the area for the Project based on availability of suitable land, interconnection suitability, minimal environmental impacts, and the surrounding community, as discussed in greater detail below:

* Land Availability and Infrastructure: Large tracts of undeveloped lands are typically utilized for utility-scale solar facilities. The Project Area is mostly agricultural land that has been cultivated for grain. The Project Area is also adjacent to nearby roads and highways--such as County Road (CR) M and U.S. Route (US) 14--that are suitable for equipment and material delivery during construction.

* Interconnection Suitability: One primary factor in site selection for utility-scale solar development is availably of existing electric infrastructure necessary to connect a project to the power grid. Preferred injection points are found where the existing electrical infrastructure is robust, thereby minimizing the interconnection facility costs and network upgrades frequently attributed to new generating facilities. Projects where land is available near points of interconnection are prioritized.

Prior to submitting an interconnection request into the Midcontinent Independent System Operator (MISO) queue, North Rock evaluated existing transmission facilities in

3

the area for available capacity and stability for a utility-scale solar project. It was determined that the Sheepskin 69-kV substation would have capacity for a solar project of at least 50 MW without triggering significant costly upgrades. On March 8, 2018, North Rock submitted an interconnection request to MISO to interconnect into the Sheepskin 69 kV substation. The North Rock Solar Project was given MISO queue number J1188. Additional details regarding the Project's interconnection status are provided in Section 2.5, below.

* Environmental Considerations: A preliminary analysis was completed to screen for environmental factors including, but not limited to, wetlands, waterways, endangered species, critical habitat, floodplain, and cultural and historic resources. The land on which the Project will be located has few environmental constraints and those factors identified can be avoided by placement of the solar photovoltaic (PV) array.

* Community: It is preferable to site solar projects in communities that welcome those projects and where landowners are interested in hosting solar facilities. The Town of Fulton and Rock County have expressed positive feedback about the Project.

2. TECHNICAL DESCRIPTION, PROJECT AREA, PANEL AND PANEL SITES, AND ANCILLARY FACILITIES

2.1 ESTIMATED SOLAR RESOURCE AND PROJECTED ENERGY PRODUCTION

To evaluate the solar energy resource for the Project, 12 months of estimated meteorological data was used. This data was developed utilizing the NREL NSRDB Typ. Met. Year PSMv3 - 2018 TMY meteo data file collected from Station ID 844313. This data was then supplemented with 23 years of derived satellite data to fill in any gaps and complete a Model Output Statistic corrected Typical Meteorological Year. This solar irradiance and climate information was then used to simulate a typical full year of production with the photovoltaic systems software ("PVSYST") analysis program.

While the maximum output of the solar farm will be 50 MWAC at the point of connection, its output may be less at any given time depending on the energy available from the sun.1 The software program PVSYST was used to simulate the energy conversion process using model files from the PV module and inverter manufacturer, historical weather data discussed above, and the parameters that apply to the solar farm. The net capacity factor for the Project is calculated to be between 23 and 25 percent, when comparing the nameplate rating (50 MWAC) to the energy forecasted from the PVSYST model.

The estimated net annual energy production is between approximately 99,000 and 105,000 megawatt hours (MWh). Actual annual energy production output will depend on final design, site specific features, and annual variability in the solar resource. Energy losses within the system include electrical losses in the AC and direct current (DC) electrical collector system, energy conversion losses within the PV inverters, step-up transformers and various other equipment, as well as losses due to soiling of the PV modules themselves due to dust, debris and snow cover. Taking those factors into account, a reasonable estimate of energy losses range from 15 to 20 percent of the maximum output, which is consistent with industry-wide estimates.
